00:39:54.336 --> 00:39:56.840
So it's 5,700 square foot,

00:39:56.907 --> 00:39:59.055
four bedrooms, seven bathrooms.

00:39:59.122 --> 00:40:00.624
-What year was it built?

00:40:00.691 --> 00:40:02.014
'62.

00:40:02.081 --> 00:40:04.273
-Okay.
So it's done with quality and pride.

00:40:04.340 --> 00:40:07.232
Oh, yeah. I'll let you in.
It's very nice. Okay.

00:40:07.299 --> 00:40:09.446
-You sure?
-This side needs to be loved on.

00:40:09.513 --> 00:40:11.094
So I'm putting this on YouTube.

00:40:11.161 --> 00:40:13.336
-You're okay with that?
-Oh, yeah.

00:40:13.403 --> 00:40:14.974
And are you gonna stay here?

00:40:15.041 --> 00:40:17.041
Alex was saying
you guys might be moving.

00:40:17.108 --> 00:40:18.906
Well, we own a business in Benton.

00:40:18.973 --> 00:40:21.327
Have you been to Benton?
Not Bentonville?

00:40:21.394 --> 00:40:23.466
-No, I haven't.
-Yeah. It's a good place.

00:40:23.533 --> 00:40:27.293
We own a business there.
So we travel just to live here.

00:40:27.360 --> 00:40:29.921
My husband does an hour to work
and an hour back.

00:40:29.988 --> 00:40:30.871
-Okay.

00:40:30.938 --> 00:40:33.602
So we've considered it over the time.

00:40:33.669 --> 00:40:35.257
But I would keep the house.

00:40:35.943 --> 00:40:38.906
Can I… and you don't have to answer this,
obviously.

00:40:38.973 --> 00:40:41.816
-What did you buy it for?
-It was $305,000.

00:40:41.883 --> 00:40:44.686
We had to put about $200,000 in it.

00:40:45.230 --> 00:40:48.141
So close the door of $500,000. Yeah.

00:40:48.208 --> 00:40:50.083
-Oh, my God.
-Yeah.

00:40:50.150 --> 00:40:51.437
$500G for this?

00:40:51.504 --> 00:40:53.633
You haven't seen it inside yet too.

00:40:53.700 --> 00:40:55.041
-Oh, my God.

00:40:55.108 --> 00:40:58.173
Just the woodwork alone,
like the people that did it,

00:40:58.240 --> 00:40:59.923
it's irreplaceable.

00:40:59.990 --> 00:41:02.921
And we're in 2026 America.

00:41:02.988 --> 00:41:03.871
Yes.

00:41:03.938 --> 00:41:05.524
This isn't 1972.

00:41:05.591 --> 00:41:08.899
No. It's great. It's such a beautiful home.
We're so blessed.

00:41:08.966 --> 00:41:10.893
-Oh, and you got a pool?
-Oh, yeah.

00:41:10.960 --> 00:41:12.136
We got a pool house.

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:14.810
It just monsooned out here.

00:41:14.877 --> 00:41:16.116
So why is it so low?

00:41:16.183 --> 00:41:18.402
Because people are just
scared of Pine Bluff?

00:41:18.469 --> 00:41:21.319
Yeah. It's just the…
what everybody says about Pine Bluff.

00:41:21.386 --> 00:41:22.983
You know, Crime Bluff.

00:41:23.050 --> 00:41:23.933
[Peter gasps]

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:26.978
-This is absolutely beautiful.
-It's all the little details.

00:41:27.045 --> 00:41:28.363
-Yeah.
-See the inside?

00:41:28.430 --> 00:41:31.530
Like it's all wrapped with copper.
The whole house is.

00:41:31.597 --> 00:41:32.480
-Wow.
-Yeah.

00:41:33.220 --> 00:41:36.491
So, these days
you'd never get a house built like this.

00:41:36.558 --> 00:41:38.148
No, no, no, no. And you know…

00:41:38.215 --> 00:41:40.460
-Not with copper, not with real metal.

00:41:40.527 --> 00:41:44.759
We've been working for about five years
at purchasing a home in Benton.

00:41:44.826 --> 00:41:47.885
And we just couldn't.
We couldn't with what I wanted.

00:41:48.740 --> 00:41:50.743
-Okay, great kitchen. Nice.

00:41:50.810 --> 00:41:53.343
Yeah, well we're kind of
updating the kitchen,

00:41:53.410 --> 00:41:57.441
but just redoing a couple things I really
don't want to take away from the house.

00:41:57.508 --> 00:42:02.801
All of the wood is like… This is not like
that foam stuff that you can buy at Lowe's.

00:42:03.380 --> 00:42:05.512
All of the work that they've done…

00:42:05.920 --> 00:42:08.743
So, it was in Arkansas Tours.

00:42:08.810 --> 00:42:10.854
The house was in the Smithsonian

00:42:11.287 --> 00:42:13.440
because of the woodwork
and the things that…

00:42:13.507 --> 00:42:14.421
-Wow.
-Yeah.

00:42:14.488 --> 00:42:16.553
Look at this beautiful floor.

00:42:16.620 --> 00:42:18.253
-Yeah, it's all marble.

00:42:18.320 --> 00:42:20.933
-What a beautiful floor. Look at this.

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:23.094
-Just all these curves.
-It's insane.

00:42:23.161 --> 00:42:26.455
They wouldn't do that these days
unless you're spending a fortune.

00:42:26.522 --> 00:42:28.447
-'Cause it would cost a fortune.
-Yeah.

00:42:28.514 --> 00:42:30.086
I love all the doors.

00:42:30.153 --> 00:42:34.002
All of these came from this place
in New York and they're just solid brass.

00:42:34.069 --> 00:42:35.654
-They're just so cool.
-Right.

00:42:35.721 --> 00:42:37.466
Yeah, everything's got quality.

00:42:37.533 --> 00:42:40.416
All of the little, you know,
the little closets that just…

00:42:40.534 --> 00:42:44.436
-Okay, if someone came up to you today
and said, okay, $700,000.

00:42:44.503 --> 00:42:49.194
I've had somebody do that
and I didn't because we've decided to stay.

00:42:50.390 --> 00:42:53.073
So, this is the room
that we spend all of our time in.

00:42:53.140 --> 00:42:54.113
This is so awesome.

00:42:54.180 --> 00:42:56.223
So, it's got two fireplaces.

00:42:56.940 --> 00:42:59.807
And then, of course,
you know, it's overlooking…

00:42:59.874 --> 00:43:01.919
-And look at these big paned windows.

00:43:01.986 --> 00:43:03.083
-Yeah.

00:43:03.150 --> 00:43:06.077
And these are original.
We changed out quite a few of them.

00:43:06.144 --> 00:43:11.072
So, for the price of the most rundown,
disgusting one bedroom

00:43:11.758 --> 00:43:13.826
in the Bay Area, California.

00:43:13.893 --> 00:43:16.318
-How much?
-Well, it'd be $500,000.

00:43:16.385 --> 00:43:18.032
-You could get this.
-Really?

00:43:18.672 --> 00:43:19.593
-Yeah.
-Wow.

00:43:19.660 --> 00:43:23.013
So, you know what I like about this too?
What I've seen in Arkansas?

00:43:23.080 --> 00:43:26.966
A lot of people are bummed out
in the country about buying a home.

00:43:27.033 --> 00:43:28.863
The American dream. I get it.

00:43:28.930 --> 00:43:30.673
-It's great owning a home.
-Yeah.

00:43:30.740 --> 00:43:34.516
But I met a guy in Little Rock.
He bought a place for like $140,000.

00:43:34.930 --> 00:43:36.448
-He's a bartender.
-Yeah.

00:43:36.515 --> 00:43:38.914
You know, this place,
you could get for $300,000.

00:43:38.981 --> 00:43:41.426
-When you got it for $300,000, right?
-Yeah.

00:43:41.493 --> 00:43:45.040
So, from what I'm seeing,
it's still possible here.

00:43:45.107 --> 00:43:46.675
-Oh, yeah.
-Right?

00:43:46.742 --> 00:43:50.283
So, Pine Bluff
has areas like any other city

00:43:50.350 --> 00:43:53.070
that you could literally
buy a house for $10,000.

00:43:53.137 --> 00:43:56.647
-I just went through those neighborhoods.
-If you're in the wrong area.

00:43:56.714 --> 00:44:00.415
But like this, and then
we've got some other areas in town.

00:44:00.482 --> 00:44:02.523
the country club's right down the road.

00:44:02.590 --> 00:44:06.078
You just don't think about those things
just because of the stigma.

00:44:06.145 --> 00:44:08.662
-You don't know until you go.
-Yeah.

00:44:08.729 --> 00:44:11.048
I saw this house,
I was actually on vacation.

00:44:11.115 --> 00:44:12.813
My cousin sent it to me.

00:44:12.880 --> 00:44:14.207
I was like, yeah.

00:44:14.274 --> 00:44:16.819
Like all these built-in things.
Those are speakers.

00:44:16.886 --> 00:44:18.853
Like old school speakers.

00:44:18.920 --> 00:44:20.389
So, they gifted us this.

00:44:20.456 --> 00:44:22.955
And I only keep this
for nostalgia, of course,

00:44:23.022 --> 00:44:25.676
but the little tube TV
from whenever they lived here.

00:44:25.743 --> 00:44:27.822
-Yeah. You got a VCR. Nice.
-Yeah.

00:44:28.770 --> 00:44:30.718
So, I grew up in foster care.

00:44:30.785 --> 00:44:33.305
And I was five
whenever I was taken from my family.

00:44:33.372 --> 00:44:35.266
And it was this little white house.

00:44:35.765 --> 00:44:39.178
And whenever my cousin sent me this house,
it was just so…

00:44:39.245 --> 00:44:40.318
It was like, wow.

00:44:40.741 --> 00:44:42.453
The Lord is so good.

00:44:42.520 --> 00:44:44.376
This is gonna be my house.

00:44:44.443 --> 00:44:47.583
From little bitty white house
going into foster care.

00:44:47.650 --> 00:44:51.136
-Wow. You went into foster care
until you're what? A late teen?

00:44:51.203 --> 00:44:52.488
15, yeah.

00:44:52.555 --> 00:44:54.032
-And then you were out?
-Yeah.

00:44:54.099 --> 00:44:55.413
-On your own?
-On my own.

00:44:55.480 --> 00:44:56.529
-At 15?
-Yeah.

00:44:57.111 --> 00:44:59.856
-How'd you make your way?
-It was hard.

00:44:59.923 --> 00:45:01.158
-Where'd you grow up?

00:45:01.939 --> 00:45:04.119
Well, have you seen Quapaw in Little Rock?

00:45:04.186 --> 00:45:05.069
-No.

00:45:05.136 --> 00:45:08.037
Quapaw area,
if you go Downtown, Little Rock,

00:45:08.104 --> 00:45:10.079
Quapaw is like the original part of it.

00:45:10.146 --> 00:45:11.799
-I think I went there.
-Yeah.

00:45:11.866 --> 00:45:14.091
So, we had an apartment there.

00:45:14.158 --> 00:45:15.946
-It's a long story.
-Okay.

00:45:16.013 --> 00:45:19.296
But yeah, my mom,
she was just not a good mom.

00:45:19.999 --> 00:45:22.344
And she had an apartment for me

00:45:22.411 --> 00:45:24.661
and she didn't have time
to take me to school,

00:45:24.728 --> 00:45:27.283
which I wasn't begging her to at 14, 15.

00:45:27.350 --> 00:45:29.981
And I met this guy,

00:45:30.048 --> 00:45:31.367
and… [laughs]

00:45:31.434 --> 00:45:34.238
my only requirement at the time
was that he drove a car.

00:45:34.305 --> 00:45:36.338
So that was pretty easy.

00:45:36.405 --> 00:45:38.930
So anyway, we were married,
had two beautiful kids.

00:45:38.997 --> 00:45:41.416
And Shane and I,
this is my second marriage,

00:45:41.483 --> 00:45:43.110
we've been married for 20 years.

00:45:43.177 --> 00:45:46.755
-Oh, congrats. What a journey.
-So we're…

00:45:47.670 --> 00:45:49.606
-So anything's possible.
-That's right.

00:45:49.673 --> 00:45:51.983
It's about mindset, a lot of it, right?

00:45:52.050 --> 00:45:55.509
Well, my personal belief is that the Lord,

00:45:56.632 --> 00:45:58.547
even in chaos, can give you joy.

00:45:59.030 --> 00:46:02.563
So I've just kind of lived that way
my whole life. Just…

00:46:02.630 --> 00:46:05.751
-So because of the Lord,
guided you through.

00:46:05.818 --> 00:46:06.701
Yeah.

00:46:06.768 --> 00:46:08.193
-Got you here.
-Yeah.

00:46:08.260 --> 00:46:10.668
Not the house, but the place.

00:46:10.735 --> 00:46:14.639
Like we go through cr*p, you know,
our lives are real, you know.

00:46:14.706 --> 00:46:16.506
-Everyone does, right?
-That's right.

00:46:16.573 --> 00:46:19.491
Everyone's got their own level
of BS they're dealing with.

00:46:19.558 --> 00:46:20.496
Yeah. Absolutely.

00:46:20.563 --> 00:46:23.328
And so, we're just thankful
for our little spot.

00:46:23.780 --> 00:46:26.542
It's not so little.
It's pretty huge, actually. Yeah.

00:46:26.609 --> 00:46:27.903
-Yeah.
-But it's great.

00:46:29.790 --> 00:46:31.840
So you said you were doing what for work?

00:46:31.908 --> 00:46:34.895
So I'm an advocate for foster children.

00:46:35.433 --> 00:46:38.856
And so what that means is
I know a lot about the fun laws.

00:46:38.923 --> 00:46:40.373
I've spoken on Capitol Hill.

00:46:40.440 --> 00:46:42.481
I've done a lot of really big things.

00:46:42.548 --> 00:46:45.549
I grew up in foster care and I want to
help those that are there now.

00:46:45.616 --> 00:46:47.322
How is it right now for kids?

00:46:47.389 --> 00:46:50.893
I hate to commodify it,
but there's a supply and demand, right?

00:46:50.960 --> 00:46:55.009
You need to have enough supply
of foster parents for the demand.

00:46:55.076 --> 00:46:56.042
Is there enough?

00:46:56.109 --> 00:47:01.400
Yeah. So if you saw
the recent numbers for just the entire US,

00:47:01.467 --> 00:47:02.911
the big number is 52.

00:47:02.978 --> 00:47:05.302
So there are 52 houses

00:47:05.369 --> 00:47:07.341
for every hundred children.

00:47:07.408 --> 00:47:08.986
So you've got a deficit.

00:47:09.053 --> 00:47:11.675
So there's just so much work to be done.

00:47:11.742 --> 00:47:15.819
If there was one thing that I would add
to the need for foster parents,

00:47:15.886 --> 00:47:17.350
it's trauma inform…

00:47:17.907 --> 00:47:20.976
Informing and training
the foster parents more.

00:47:21.043 --> 00:47:21.926
-Okay.

00:47:21.993 --> 00:47:25.721
You get these kids like me, you know,
I had a lot of stuff to deal with.

00:47:25.788 --> 00:47:28.605
I was abused
before I came into foster care.

00:47:28.672 --> 00:47:30.993
So you're dealing with
an abused five-year-old.

00:47:31.060 --> 00:47:33.543
-You're not dealing with a five-year old.
-Right.

00:47:33.610 --> 00:47:36.440
So they really need
trauma informed training.

00:47:36.507 --> 00:47:41.108
And people just love, you know,
they're called to love and they do.

00:47:41.175 --> 00:47:44.412
And then they have these kids
that have these big problems.

00:47:44.863 --> 00:47:47.562
And they don't know how to deal with it.
So training.

00:47:48.057 --> 00:47:49.515
-Okay.
-Training is a big one.

00:47:49.582 --> 00:47:53.158
You can have a hundred houses
for a hundred kids and it not work out.

00:47:53.225 --> 00:47:55.957
'Cause you can unadopt a child
from foster care.

00:47:56.604 --> 00:47:58.217
So they can go into foster care.

00:47:58.284 --> 00:48:02.751
You can adopt them and then realize they're
not good for your home and send them back.

00:48:02.818 --> 00:48:04.877
-And then that damages the kid even more.

00:48:04.944 --> 00:48:09.276
I've heard of some two and three times
just adopted back and forth.

00:48:09.343 --> 00:48:12.970
-And Pine Bluff, how is it for kids
in this city or just really depends?

00:48:13.037 --> 00:48:15.274
Pine Bluff is a very poverished area.

00:48:15.341 --> 00:48:17.090
So we have a lot of need.

00:48:17.157 --> 00:48:19.091
-You have a lot of need? Okay.
-Yeah.

00:48:19.158 --> 00:48:21.575
-So you're trying to help.
-Yeah. Any way I can.

00:48:21.642 --> 00:48:22.656
-Cool.
-Yeah.

00:48:22.723 --> 00:48:23.923
Stephanie.

00:48:23.990 --> 00:48:26.993
-So nice to meet you. Glad you popped in.
-Great to meet you.

00:48:27.060 --> 00:48:30.503
-Great to meet you. It's because of Alex.
-Yeah. Alex is a cool guy.

00:48:30.570 --> 00:48:31.807
To Pine Bluff.

00:48:31.874 --> 00:48:34.031
-Okay. Sorry. I didn't have that on camera.

00:48:34.098 --> 00:48:36.226
You said people from Saline County…

00:48:36.293 --> 00:48:40.363
Ask me, "Man, people move
from Pine Bluff, not to Pine Bluff."

00:48:40.430 --> 00:48:42.530
[Alex] I've been hearing that all my life.

00:48:42.597 --> 00:48:44.233
And this is just a hidden jewel.

00:48:44.300 --> 00:48:46.486
I mean, man, just the camaraderie.

00:48:46.950 --> 00:48:49.001
I lived in Saline County 15 years.

00:48:49.068 --> 00:48:52.621
Same house, knew all my neighbors.
Knew people all around me.

00:48:52.688 --> 00:48:56.305
But this here
is a different level of people.

00:48:57.210 --> 00:48:58.953
-You know all your neighbors here?

00:48:59.020 --> 00:49:02.074
-Every neighbor in here.
-So you guys look out for each other?

00:49:02.141 --> 00:49:04.941
This whole neighborhood
has a Christmas party every year.

00:49:05.008 --> 00:49:06.273
Everybody comes.

00:49:06.340 --> 00:49:09.783
We block all this off right here
and have a fall fest.

00:49:09.850 --> 00:49:11.530
Neighbors, like not all of them,

00:49:11.597 --> 00:49:14.436
but a large majority of them
will meet here.

00:49:14.503 --> 00:49:17.767
We'll all dress up like we had
Wizard of Oz this past year.

00:49:17.834 --> 00:49:22.135
And we had Wizard of Oz playing
on a big jumbo screen in his yard.

00:49:22.598 --> 00:49:23.932
And had the little deal.

00:49:23.999 --> 00:49:28.531
Had a little photo op set up
for the kids to come up and do a photo op.

00:49:28.957 --> 00:49:30.803
-Just super cool.
-That is amazing.

00:49:30.870 --> 00:49:32.301
Even when we come down here,

00:49:32.368 --> 00:49:35.335
I didn't even have any idea
how cool the people…

00:49:35.889 --> 00:49:38.221
Just doing life with you.

00:49:38.680 --> 00:49:42.383
You know, you have a problem? [snaps]
Man, I could make a phone call…

00:49:42.450 --> 00:49:46.676
If I had that tree go down, there would be
15 people over here with chainsaws.

00:49:46.743 --> 00:49:48.436
-You guys are like Amish.
-Yeah.

00:49:48.503 --> 00:49:51.539
Just all kind of gathered up, man. Hey.

00:49:51.606 --> 00:49:54.822
-You move a barn.
-Get in where you fit in. [laughs]

00:49:55.690 --> 00:49:57.593
Great stuff. Thank you so much.

00:49:57.660 --> 00:49:59.063
-Good to see you, buddy.
-Yes, sir.

00:49:59.130 --> 00:50:01.546
-You guys be safe.
-Take care, Shane.

00:50:02.270 --> 00:50:05.373
Man, my head is spinning
from not expecting to see this today.

00:50:05.440 --> 00:50:07.558
-Yeah, dude. What a grand old house.

00:50:12.372 --> 00:50:15.943
[Peter] It's interesting coming from
the outside with Pine Bluff, right?

00:50:16.010 --> 00:50:19.245
I said earlier that
everything's always going in a cycle.

00:50:19.312 --> 00:50:21.514
-Places go up, they go down.
-Right.

00:50:21.581 --> 00:50:23.654
I could imagine potentially,

00:50:23.721 --> 00:50:26.442
maybe I'm being just
optimistic in the moment,

00:50:26.509 --> 00:50:30.911
but 10, 20, maybe 30 years,
this place is just…

00:50:30.978 --> 00:50:33.474
It could have a totally different feel.

00:50:33.541 --> 00:50:35.405
It definitely has a lot of potential.

00:50:35.472 --> 00:50:39.766
And I think that the more awareness
that gets brought to Pine Bluff,

00:50:40.473 --> 00:50:45.253
the more that businesses may see it
and want to come back and build again.

00:50:45.320 --> 00:50:49.342
-It's just the crime has to get down.
-Absolutely. That's the biggest problem.

00:50:49.409 --> 00:50:51.259
Nobody wants to move into high crime.

00:50:51.326 --> 00:50:54.032
And I get it.
It's what part of town you're in.

00:50:54.684 --> 00:50:57.055
-But overall, it's a tough sell.
-Yeah.

00:50:57.122 --> 00:50:59.888
Like, to tell your…
Oh, look at how cool that place is.

00:50:59.955 --> 00:51:02.053
Oh, man. I love that place.

00:51:02.120 --> 00:51:06.548
It's a tough sell being like, hey, wifey,
let's move to the place with, you know…

00:51:06.615 --> 00:51:08.958
-Yeah, right.
-…an outrageous homicide rate.

00:51:09.025 --> 00:51:09.908
Yeah.

00:51:10.508 --> 00:51:12.912
Tough sell.
But again, everything's regionalized.

00:51:12.979 --> 00:51:16.373
It's like where you're at
and where things are happening.

